WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Today is Monday, July 18, 2011. My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:32.000
I'm in Midtown Manhattan with a video videographer John Bishop to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:40.000
which is an undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:51.000
And we're just really delighted and honored to be with you today, Professor Jack Greenberg, to talk about some very, very interesting Civil Rights history and your role in a lot of that history.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Thanks for meeting with us.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:08.000
I thought I might start and have you just talk a little bit about how you evaluated the choice to join NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund as a law school graduate in 49?

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Well, implicitly, I really made that choice before 49. I'd started a Columbia Law School with no thought of being a Civil Rights lawyer because there was no such thing.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:34.000
I thought I would maybe do labor law or things that later would come under the label of Civil Rights.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:42.000
But I had a professor at the time, Walter Gellhorn, who gave a seminar, which he called Legal Survey.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And in Legal Survey, students worked for Civil Liberty, Civil Rights Lawyers, again, that label hadn't attached to anyone at that time.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:03.000
It was sort of a precursor of clinical legal education. We were working on real cases.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And I saw this course listed on the Bulletin Board. And I immediately ran our Silicon Recall, running up two flights of stairs.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:27.000
It was Professor Gellhorn's office. It was coming and rolled in the course. A curious bit of history that this Smithsonian would be interested in is why he named it Legal Survey.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:35.000
He said if he called it Civil Rights or Civil Liberties, the faculty might not permit him to teach it.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Because in those days, if you were a Civil Libertarian or Civil Rights advocate, you ran the risk of being called a Communist.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And in fact, Professor Gellhorn himself was summoned down to Congress on two occasions, to swear, I am not and never have been a member of the Communist Party.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So I took this course. And since the subject matter of the course has changed from week to week, depending on the cases you were working on, I took it for four semesters.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:16.000
And it became chairman of the student body taking that course.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:27.000
As I got out of law school, well, to make the long story very short, I had worked on some legal defense when cases.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And there weren't a lot of lawyers doing that. Legal defense when at that time had three or four of the lawyers.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:48.000
The American Civil Liberties Union, which now has hundreds of lawyers, had a single lawyer. There were three Jewish organizations that respectively had three and one and one lawyers.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:55.000
And that's all there was in the whole US, except some individual lawyers who handled some civil rights cases.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Anyway, one of the lawyers at NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, her name was Marian Wynne Perry, was Marian Wynne Perry.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:14.000
And it got some official position with New York State, and it required him to be an opening new year.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:26.000
And so she resigned, and it was an opening. And the third in March of last, the whole of the yellow one to recommend somebody, and he recommended me.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:38.000
And so that's all I got there. So I was at a disposition to do it, because I took this seminar for four semesters, but I hadn't planned to do it.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:45.000
He's not exactly planning for a career in which there were six lawyers in the whole country doing it.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
Okay, we're back after a short break.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Well, if I was a Greenberg, I thought I would extend the theme by asking to describe that small band of NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund attorneys.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.000
I'm obviously under the very good Marshall's direction there, and in 49 when you join, as you say, it's just a couple of folks.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Right, there was so good. Even at that point, they had become a national figure, because he'd won the restrictive covenant cases.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:33.000
So I'd describe it if you asked me to. He'd won some of the big voting rights case, and also, he had his first assistant who was Robert L. Carter, who was a judge here in New York.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
I had a time of retire.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Another fellow called Franklin H. Williams, who later went on to another position in the NAACP, and then became ambassador to Ghana, and the head of the foundation, Phelps Stokes Foundation.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:10.000
That was it, and it was me. There was also a woman there who was a full-time sociologist. I'm truly only law officer in the world, a sociologist, honest staff.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
That was it.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:30.000
At that time, I might say, we were part of the NAACP. We were a separate independent part, though the independence caused some tension between us and Roy Wilkins, the head of the NAACP.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
But nevertheless, independent.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:50.000
In 1957, we were related to tax exemption. We spun off, became entirely independent as the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And then later created some different kinds of tension.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Let me ask, as a young lawyer, you were very quickly in the midst of a lot of very significant litigation in schools, and particularly in schools, obviously in the early 50s.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
I think you and Robert L. Carter tried the Kansas schools case out in Topeka, Kansas.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:16.000
That's right.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Can you share some recollections of that experience?

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Oh, yeah. Well, I think the things you remember about the case and not the important things, because the important things are part of history, so you don't have to be mentioning them again.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:39.000
The Kansas had a peculiar statute. It was an Kansas school segregation statute.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:08:00.000
The schools were required to be segregated by law in Kansas, high schools, or high school systems, could opt to be segregated, and Kansas had taken that option.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:05.000
We tried the case on two different tracks, as we did, all the other cases.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:14.000
That is to show that the black schools were not equal to the white schools, in which we make all tangible, measurable respects.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:26.000
Number of books, teachers, salaries, numbers, where feet, gymnasium, playing ground, curriculum, laboratories, things like that.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:40.000
But then we also tried it on the basis of urging the court, with the help of expert witnesses, to understand that segregation itself constituted inequality.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:58.000
I know you probably have told this story many times, but let me ask you just to recall your reaction when the Brown v. Board of Education finally came down in May of 54.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:05.000
Well, that was a long time from the argument, which was 50-51, really.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:14.000
And then we appealed to the Supreme Court in 52, and then argued two more times after that.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
Everybody was kind of stunned by it.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:29.000
We won lots of cases before in the sense of big rocket celebrations, and we just sort of silenced the sentence that everybody would have.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:34.000
I think stunned is the only word, a cosmic decision.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And later turned out to be even more cosmic, then.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:44.000
We understood we were the case, the challenge, school segregation.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:50.000
It turned out the decision swept away all state-imposed segregation.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:10:08.000
Were you surprised by the vehement of the pattern of reaction that arose in the late 50s across the South to early efforts to desegregate schools?

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:27.000
That's right, there were other cases like that that had been won in the following higher education law schools, graduate schools, voting, and then in lower courses, things like golf courses, beaches, theaters.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:34.000
And there was sort of grudging acceptance of those.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:41.000
And the cases, those earlier cases did not involve any mass numbers of people.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:55.000
The higher education cases involved one or two people, but integrating a school system, large numbers, and more horrible to the segregationists were.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:59.000
And then women going to school together, boys and girls.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:07.000
The biggest taboo was any kind of contact between the sexes.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:20.000
I'm interested to have you talk a little bit about how you measure the landscape of possibility when you became director council in 61.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
Well by then a lot of things had happened.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:30.000
61, the civil rights movement had begun.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And the students were being sitting in North Carolina, as you well know, and elsewhere in the South.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.000
And it was picking up like wildfire all over the country.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:56.000
And they were being arrested. And there were no ready defenses for them, because they had never been necessary to defend anybody against anything like that.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:05.000
But we understood the Constitution and leave Alaska pretty well.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:11.000
And so we were ready with a bunch of defenses.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And we, I might say, we ended up by the time the civil rights movement.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I don't know what I've ever ended by the time it reached some measurable stopping point.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:31.000
We represented about 3500 people and got them all acquitted.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:40.000
And neglected as we were talking there for a minute about the late 50s, I wanted to ask and have you, um, discussed, you published in 59 race relations in American law.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
That's right. Which was an unprecedented volume.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:54.000
Can you talk a little bit about the effort to do that work, to do that volume and what you were trying to do with it?

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:01.000
Well a lot of these things, you don't have any ambitions beyond the thing itself, because you can't tell what's going to happen.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:07.000
But I was practicing civil rights law, and I was impressed by the fact that there was no book on civil rights law.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:14.000
And I was handling cases in all the areas that the book covered.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:27.000
Essentially I took my knowledge of those cases and put them into the book, which was the first one in my civil rights law since about 1919.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
What reaction did the book receive?

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:36.000
It was curious in some ways. They've got excellent reviews.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:45.000
But it was considered to be a hot topic. For example, the Columbia Law Review did something I haven't seen them do or any other law review.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Before, since they published a pro and anti-review as if we were a controversial subject.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:11.000
And then there was some academics who had used on civil rights.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:23.000
There was one Herbert Wechsler, a famous article called Toward Neutral Principles of Constitutional Law".

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:32.000
And then there was a legal philosopher at NYU, Edmond Cahn, who wrote a book.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:39.000
Essentially an article, anyway, attacking the Brown v. Board of Education for its use of social science data.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:45.000
Anyway, I didn't see how I could have anything against what I'd written.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And it would be quite a clue to get them to review the book.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
So I sent them a copy and asked what they would review.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And he called me and asked me to come to his office.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And he said, he wants them to know that he thought the book was an excellent book.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:09.000
But he didn't feel he could review it objectively with his son.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.000
He was white and married a black woman.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
I said, well, I didn't think that should make any difference.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:23.000
I really didn't want to go.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:27.000
Can you move again to the early 60s?

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:31.000
You've written and used the phrase of movement in some respects.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And those after February 1960, really shifted from the courts and into the streets there for many years.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
Oh, yeah.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And of course, you traveled extensively, had been traveling extensively from New York, from the time you joined the LDF.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Are there any episodes or memories that really stand out in your mind as exemplary or particularly vivid in recalling those early years of the 60s when the movement was really active in the streets?

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:10.000
Well, part of the traveling was, of course, going on railroads or airplanes.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:15.000
And the railroads were segregated at the beginning.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:25.000
Airplanes weren't but a good many airport terminals were even north-throw line, even at federal facilities.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
So that was something no-worthy.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:37.000
And we brought a number of cases, a fair number of cases, to desegregate airports and protocol bringing a case.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
Desegregate in the airport in Atlanta.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:48.000
Plainfacures there, the name of Koch, so it was Koch against City of Atlanta, which is the home of Koch of Koch.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:55.000
And I brought a case against the airport in New Orleans.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:05.000
My co-counsel was A.P. Tureaud, who were a period of time, was the only black lawyer in New Orleans.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:14.000
A Tura, well, I didn't think it was his granddaughter, I think he was two-year-old, so that's been his daughter.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:19.000
He brought his granddaughter to the airport after he won the case.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.000
And she ran off just gleefully.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
She was able to buy an ice cream cone there.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.000
Something she'd never been able to do before.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:38.000
You mentioned Attorney Tura, which reminds me of the network of cooperating attorneys at the LVF developed over the years.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:46.000
And pioneering black attorneys in the South, who would very courageously take cases and conjunction with Legal Defense Fund.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:18:00.000
But I also want to ask, in 63 on your own initiative as Director Counsel, you launched a new training program that would become quite a significant mechanism for extending the numbers of black attorneys in the South.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
Oh, yeah, I'm talking about that a little bit.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:08.000
There were a lot of cities where there was no black lawyer at all, or maybe one.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:12.000
But an amazing number that was done at all.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
And I got some money from a foundation.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:24.000
The black lawyer was a go set up a practice in a place where there were no black lawyers.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:31.000
We give him $10,000 to buy a typewriter, a rug, and some law books.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
We got some great stars out of that.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:39.000
There were Julius Chambers.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And then one of Mel Watt.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
No, what?

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:51.000
No, what?

00:18:51.000 --> 00:19:00.000
And then another congressman in Georgia, in the world, his name, I think even the moment,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:09.000
he didn't want to, he wanted to set a practice in Atlanta, but by then there were a handful of black lawyers in Atlanta.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
And I originally went to some places.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:12.000
He went to Columbus.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
He was the only black lawyer.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:18.000
And he's now the congressman from...

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
from Columbus.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:23.000
Marian Wright Edelman also was in Columbus.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:24.000
Marian Wright Edelman?

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:29.000
Yes, (Marian) Wright was one of the aces. She was terrific.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:41.000
And in the run-up towards the Civil Rights Act of 64, particularly saved by 63 when Kennedy has introduced legislation,

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:46.000
some bill appears increasingly likely to clear the congress.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:53.000
It's always not perfectly certain, but there's momentum in that direction, particularly after Kennedy's assassination, obviously.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And the Legal Defense Fund, under your direction, is really working hard to craft a litigation program that will encompass all of this new legal terrain.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.000
That's right.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:12.000
And I'd love to have you describe how you were thinking about new opportunities and what you, the scope of what you hoped maybe to be able to do.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:20.000
Well, one of the things that covered the public accommodation was restaurants, bar, theaters, and so forth.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:32.000
That was pretty easy, because the ice cream parlors and restaurants were happy to get the business.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:38.000
People would say that the market would take care of it, but the market did not take care of it.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:43.000
Nobody wanted to stick his neck out first.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:53.000
So we did not have a lot of relief, no real resistance. There was some emphasis on subterfuges.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:59.000
A lot of hotels set up private clubs within the hotel.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:09.000
And I would recall going to a town and being white, checking in the hotel, and being a hand at a membership card in the club,

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:16.000
and just sort of came with being white and registering in the hotel.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:20.000
And the black person registered with me, never been.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Well, that was pretty transparent, so it took a little bit of a while to figure out that's always going on.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:33.000
The public accommodation was just titled to easy.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:45.000
Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 was employment, and that, of course, we were opposed not only to employers who may not have wanted to employ blacks.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:48.000
But many of them didn't care.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:56.000
We'll be just as happy to employ blacks as employ whites, but we had a confront the fact that the labor unions,

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:10.000
which on the national level, were very pro civil rights, on the local level were segregated, white locals and black locals.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:18.000
And white locals in one, blacks in, and black locals often didn't want to lose their members to the white local.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
So that was a problem.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:27.000
We had some of our bitterest cases against the labor unions.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:30.000
Are you feeling comfortable enough for the white and the heat now?

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.000
Okay.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:37.000
We're back after short break.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:46.000
I'll come back to ask another question or two about Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 employment later in the interview,

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:53.000
obviously you were attempting in those years to find some way forward with schools.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:23:05.000
And Title VI helped maybe a little bit on that front, but the school's question would remain very difficult for the late 60s.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:08.000
That's right.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:15.000
A lot of white people didn't want to think it's the old school of black kids.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:25.000
And it didn't take a lot to stir up enough opposition.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:36.000
So we got an order to desegate the schools, they'd be resistance, and they'd be litigated, it was very vigorously.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:47.000
And none would involve schools, but the real estate values that depend upon the schools in the neighborhood,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:54.000
who involved a graduate or a property people alone.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:24:02.000
And these cases were vigorously litigated and became a subject of big political fights.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:10.000
They called it Southern Strategy. He was going to be opposed to integration.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:16.000
He had no ideological convictions about this.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:23.000
He just assumed he segregated, and non-secretly he wanted to do it, would work for him.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:32.000
After we took a case of Supreme Court, essentially defeating him and the Congress won the case.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:41.000
He didn't get in the way, and we had very widespread desegregation, Alexander v. Holmes County Board of Education.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:47.000
We really enjoyed taking that case.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:55.000
It's a great example of how the laws, all legal documents are interconnected.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:25:10.000
The way the case came up was we had won some cases which indicated that the next round of cases might lead to a certain kind of conflict.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:18.000
Supreme Court decision, that score, even a court of appeal decision, that schools had to be desegregated immediately.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:32.000
And we're Nixon, or rather Senator Senator John C. Stennis, after whom a recent aircraft carrier has been named.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:43.000
Stennis, so this is going to happen. He refused to bring the armed services appropriation built to the floor of the Senate.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:53.000
Because he told the President that his people in Mississippi need him down there to commune with him.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:07.000
Nixon had to ask his secretary of health education, a welfare, to ask the court of appeals to send the cases back to the district court without deciding him.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:16.000
And in the district court, then reconsider whether or not they should order immediate desegregation.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
And that's what happened.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:34.000
His secretary, I think Robert H. Finch was his name, asked the court of appeals, who's the Justice Department, to not decide the cases.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:46.000
Well, at that point, he were option to go with the Supreme Court as very limited because the law is that Supreme Court here cases from a final judgment.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:51.000
And the thing that Nixon was asking for was that there be no final judgment.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:59.000
So we had to appeal from the absence of the final judgment, the decision of the final judgment.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:05.000
Well, there is an ancient common law writ called certiorari.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:15.000
It's not the rid of certiorari, that's in a statute which Supreme Court uses to review almost every case it gets.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:22.000
But there's another statute which says that all the writs on the common law are available in the federal courts.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:28.000
And the ancient rid of certiorari, not the statutory certiorari, but for the common law certiorari.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:31.000
It says you can bring any case to any court you want.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:36.000
No, it doesn't happen very often, it doesn't happen successfully.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:43.000
So I still recall what I call Marshal Foch telling the staff.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:50.000
My left flank is in certiorari, my right flank is under attack, my center collapses.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:56.000
And as Marshall Farge said at the second battle of the marne, my attack.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:01.000
And we did, and the court agreed to hear and rule with us.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:12.000
The further high water mark on schools, of course, would be Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education, the Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education Charlotte Schools case 1971.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:19.000
And I wonder if you can share your recollections with Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education case and it's significant, particularly on bus fare.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:27.000
Well, Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education was the first substance of case, the court heard, and I decided to get it.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:50.000
And Chief Chief Justice Earl Warren Burger wrote a very long-guard opinion in which he called for quotas and busing and integration of teachers and everything that any civil rights advocate ever asked for.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:57.000
That was his first opinion after Nixon had appointed him.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:11.000
So Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education, but as the case began in the Supreme Court, it was not at all certain we would win the case.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Following the argument, the preliminary vote among the judges was that they would uphold the lower court, they would not enter the order we finally saw.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:40.000
But as the conference is among the judges went on, Berger, who was the leader of a minority decision, found himself outvoted by the other judges.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:47.000
(Chief Justice) Earl Warren told me. I was told of all the parties. He said, there he stood naked.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:57.000
And he had a turn this evening.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.000
Let's take a brief break.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:09.000
We're back after short break. You were just saying that Chief Chief Justice Earl Warren had remarked to you that Chief Chief Justice Earl Warren Burger stood naked.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:18.000
So no vote. Well, he's in the dissent. But if he's in the dissent, he can't decide the opinion.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:26.000
And he wants to control the opinion. So he switched his vote and decided to vote. There's a court went, so he could have signed the opinion to himself.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:33.000
Which is what he did. And he signed it to himself. But he wrote something in the last paragraph of the opinion.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:42.000
I said, one of these days, this is going to have to come to an end. And were they going to reconsider it? And not going to require anybody to do anything.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:53.000
Something that couldn't really predict how it was going to come out. But after about 10, 15 years, that's what happened. The line on that last paragraph was gone.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:31:06.000
I want to ask, thinking about schools, I know the LVF I think was only in one of these two cases. But I'm interested in your thoughts about thinking about how the schools question arked forward from Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:14.000
As you say, it kind of maybe reached a high water in around 1980 or so. And then the numbers shifted back. And the court shifted back on the question.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:23.000
But I'm thinking about Milliken v. Bradley v. Bradley in 74 in San Antonio Independent School District v. San Antonio Independent School District v. Rodriguez in 75, the first being the Metropolitan Consultation question, obviously.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:32.000
And the second one, Alex San Antonio being the funding question. And I'm interested in your thoughts on those cases and how you gauge their significance.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:53.000
Well, Milliken v. Bradley v. Bradley was significant in that it made the distinguishing point between city and suburbs. Just the political boundary between them.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:32:06.000
It was obviously he had two families living each like 50 yards on the US side of the boundary line. The distance is not very great.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:16.000
Two different political systems, one for one county, one for another. But he didn't work that out.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:30.000
So obviously the court was making the boundary the city and the suburbs having separate different kinds of school systems.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:35.000
And that was really a political decision.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
Excuse me one second.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:45.000
We had to break there for a moment. You were talking about Milliken v. Bradley v. Bradley.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
So the decision to make.

